{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472332"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:56:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:56:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1240"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1240"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.06,0.02,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58783"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1240"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44189"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"627"},{"type":"tags","id":"1214"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44045"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58783"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA mother presents to her GP with her two-year-old son. The boy has a painless lesion on his arm which was initially not present at birth but developed within the first few weeks of life (Image). The mother is concerned about the appearance of the lesion and would like to know exactly what it is and if it could be cancerous. She also wants to know if it could be removed as it is not appealing to look at and her son is starting kindergarten soon. The mother reports that the lesion grew rapidly over the boy\u0027s first months of life but has remained a similar size since around two months old.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infantile haemangioma","Pyogenic granuloma","Arteriovenous malformation","Naevus flammeus","Dermatofibroma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis lesion is a \u003Cstrong\u003Einfantile haemangioma\u003C/strong\u003E, also referred to as \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003Estrawberry naevus\u003C/strong\u003E\u0027. It is a benign lesion which presents during the first few weeks after birth. These lesions are present in 3-10% of all infants, and are the result of abnormal vascular endothelial cell development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost of these lesions develop over the first days-months of the infant\u0027s life, then undergo complete involution. Approximately 50% of these lesions will disappear by the age of 5 years and 70% by the age of 7 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost infantile haemangiomas do not need medical treatment, other than to reassure the parents that the lesion will usually spontaneously regress and completely involute.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyogenic granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E are also benign vascular tumours but are rapidly growing and are typically on the face or hands, not the arm (Image 1). They are associated with easy bleeding. These lesions are often polypoid and lobulated and may ulcerate. They are uncommon in children of this age and are not present at birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArteriovenous malformations \u003C/strong\u003Eare abnormal connections between arteries and veins that develop during fetal development. They are often below the skin or in deeper tissues, but can be closer to the dermis and cause a red bulging lesion (Image 2). Unlike capillary haemangiomas, these lesions appear to protrude in to the skin from deeper structures and grow over time rather than appearing to be on top of the skin. They are not often visibly present at birth and do not regress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaevus flammeus\u003C/strong\u003E are also red lesions seen at birth and infancy, also called port wine stains (Image 3). They are benign vascular malformations of the dermis. Unlike capillary haemangiomas, port wine stains are typically flat, blanching pink/red patches and are not raised/dome-like as seen in the photograph in the scenario. They darken with age and do not spontaneously regress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatofibromas\u003C/strong\u003E are small lesions that are either skin coloured or brown unlike that shown in the scenario. They do not often likely grow larger than 10mm in diameter (Image 4).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Capillary haemangiomas are benign skin lesions present at birth that often undergo complete involution by 5-7 years old.","These lesions do not need to be removed as most will spontaneously involute by 5-7 years of age","Reassurance and parental education is the mainstay of treatment for capillary haemangiomas"],"references":["Satterfield KR, Chambers CB. Current treatment and management of infantile hemangiomas. Survey of Ophthalmology. 2019;64(5):608\u201318."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44189"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1240"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17919"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21122"},{"type":"media","id":"2